As shown in Fig. 4(a, b, c), upon incorporating W-CDs, the open circuit potential undergoes a pronounced downward shift, eventually plateauing at a stable level, indicating that the Cu surface has attained a stabilized state. Fig. 4(d, e, f) presents the Tafel plot at various conditions. As the concentration of W-CDs increased, a downward trend was observed in the corrosion current density (i

                           corr
                        ), suggesting that W-CDs effectively function as a barrier on the copper interface, hindering the corrosive solution from penetrating and degrading the copper substrate [77,78]. Furthermore, the cathodic segment of the Tafel curve exhibited a consistent pattern, demonstrate that the fundamental reaction dynamics at the cathode remained unaltered despite the inclusion of W-CDs. This adsorption likely led to the development of a dense adsorption layer, subsequently causing the anodic region to undergo passivation [79,80]. It is important to note that passivation area reduces as temperature rises, indicating that temperature will quicken W-CD molecule thermal motion and cause W-CDs on the copper electrode to desorb.
